  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a felony in the United States and in many other countries. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money (from activities such as drug trafficking, fraud, or other criminal enterprises) appear legitimate by disguising its true origin. This is done through a series of complex transactions and financial maneuvers.\n\nIn the United States, money laundering is primarily prosecuted under the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**. Penalties for money laundering can include:\n\n- **Criminal fines**: Up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the money laundering, whichever is greater.\n- **Imprisonment**: Up to 20 years in federal prison.\n- **Additional penalties**: Forfeiture of assets involved in or derived from the illegal activity.\n\nThe severity of the punishment often depends on the amount of money involved, the nature of the underlying criminal activity, and the defendant\u2019s role in the money laundering scheme. It\u2019s important to note that even attempting to launder money or conspiring to do so can result in felony charges.\n\nIf you or someone you know is facing such charges, it\u2019s crucial to seek legal counsel immediately.",
